bug_report.RootCause:
1) Faulty conditional logic in astropy/nddata/mixins/ndarithmetic.py, NDArithmeticMixin._arithmetic_mask: the method's branches can fall through to calling the mask handler with operand.mask == None. The relevant code is (excerpt):

   if (
       self.mask is None and operand is not None and operand.mask is None
   ) or handle_mask is None:
       return None
   elif self.mask is None and operand is not None:
       return deepcopy(operand.mask)
   elif operand is None:
       return deepcopy(self.mask)
   else:
       return handle_mask(self.mask, operand.mask, **kwds)

   Because the code only explicitly handles the cases where self.mask is None (and operand.mask None) or operand is None, it does not treat the case "self.mask is non-None && operand is not None && operand.mask is None" as "exactly one mask present". In that scenario the code reaches the else branch and invokes handle_mask(self.mask, operand.mask) where operand.mask is None; handlers that expect two non-None mask arrays (e.g. numpy.bitwise_or) will raise TypeError.

2) NDData construction and scalar-wrapping semantics: NDData (and NDDataRef via NDData subclassing) default mask to None when no mask is supplied (NDData.__init__ signature mask=None and later self.mask = mask). The arithmetic prep/boxing code converts scalar and non-NDData operands to the NDData-subclass by calling cls(operand) (see _prepare_then_do_arithmetic). As a result, a scalar operand becomes an NDData-like instance whose mask attribute is None, which makes the failing case common in scalar arithmetic (operand is not None, operand.mask is None). Both the conditional asymmetry in (1) and the NDData mask default combine to produce the observed TypeError.

3) Diagnostic semantics violated (correct/expected mask-combination behaviour, stated as diagnostic facts):
   - If handle_mask is None -> result mask is None.
   - If both operands have mask == None -> result mask is None.
   - If exactly one operand has a non-None mask -> the result mask should be a copy of the present mask (i.e. do not call a two-argument handler with None).
   - Only invoke a two-operand mask handler (e.g., handle_mask(m1, m2, ...)) when both operand masks are non-None.

4) Investigation gap: the scalar-to-NDData/NDDataRef wrapping path is invoked via cls(operand) in NDArithmeticMixin._prepare_then_do_arithmetic, which produces operand instances whose mask attribute is None by default; I did not inspect any deeper wrapper variations or external callers that might produce nonstandard mask shapes/values. Confirming that all wrapper call sites and alternate NDData constructors always use mask==None (and not e.g. an array-like of None or other sentinel) would fully validate every call site that can hit the failing branch.

